If formula_29, then formula_22 is in fact a norm. 
However, seminorms are useful in that they enable us to construct Fréchet spaces, as follows:

To construct a Fréchet space, one typically starts with a vector space formula_1 and defines a countable family of seminorms formula_32 on formula_1 with the following two properties:
* if formula_34 and formula_35 for all formula_36 then formula_37;
* if formula_38 is a sequence in formula_1 which is Cauchy with respect to each seminorm formula_40 then there exists formula_34 such that formula_38 converges to formula_20 with respect to each seminorm formula_44

Then the topology induced by these seminorms (as explained above) turns formula_1 into a Fréchet space; the first property ensures that it is Hausdorff, and the second property ensures that it is complete. 
A translation-invariant complete metric inducing the same topology on formula_1 can then be defined by
