==Examples==

===From pure functional analysis===

* Every Banach space is a Fréchet space, as the norm induces a translation-invariant metric and the space is complete with respect to this metric.
* The space formula_55 of all real valued sequences (also denoted formula_56) becomes a Fréchet space if we define the formula_57-th seminorm of a sequence to be the absolute value of the formula_57-th element of the sequence. Convergence in this Fréchet space is equivalent to element-wise convergence.

===From smooth manifolds===

===From holomorphicity===

Not all vector spaces with complete translation-invariant metrics are Fréchet spaces. An example is the space formula_59 with formula_60 
Although this space fails to be locally convex, it is an F-space.

==Properties and further notions==

If a Fréchet space admits a continuous norm then all of the seminorms used to define it can be replaced with norms by adding this continuous norm to each of them. 
A Banach space, formula_61 formula_62 with formula_1 compact, and formula_64 all admit norms, while formula_55 and formula_66 do not. 

A closed subspace of a Fréchet space is a Fréchet space. 
A quotient of a Fréchet space by a closed subspace is a Fréchet space. 
The direct sum of a finite number of Fréchet spaces is a Fréchet space. 

A product of countably many Fréchet spaces is always once again a Fréchet space. However, an arbitrary product of Fréchet spaces will be a Fréchet space if and only if all for at most countably many of them are trivial (that is, have dimension 0). Consequently, a product of uncountably many non-trivial Fréchet spaces can not be a Fréchet space (indeed, such a product is not even metrizable because its origin can not have a countable neighborhood basis). So for example, if formula_67 is any set and formula_1 is any non-trivial Fréchet space (such as formula_69 for instance), then the product formula_70 is a Fréchet space if and only if formula_71 is a countable set. 

Several important tools of functional analysis which are based on the Baire category theorem remain true in Fréchet spaces; examples are the closed graph theorem and the open mapping theorem. 
The open mapping theorem implies that if formula_72 are topologies on formula_1 that make both formula_74 and formula_75 into complete metrizable TVSs (such as Fréchet spaces) and if one topology is finer or coarser than the other then they must be equal (that is, if formula_76).

Every bounded linear operator from a Fréchet space into another topological vector space (TVS) is continuous. 

There exists a Fréchet space formula_1 having a bounded subset formula_78 and also a dense vector subspace formula_79 such that formula_78 is contained in the closure (in formula_1) of any bounded subset of formula_82 

All Fréchet spaces are stereotype spaces. In the theory of stereotype spaces Fréchet spaces are dual objects to Brauner spaces. 
All metrizable Montel spaces are separable. A separable Fréchet space is a Montel space if and only if each weak-* convergent sequence in its continuous dual converges is strongly convergent. 

The strong dual space formula_83 of a Fréchet space (and more generally, of any metrizable locally convex space) formula_1 is a DF-space. 
The strong dual of a DF-space is a Fréchet space. 
The strong dual of a reflexive Fréchet space is a bornological space and a Ptak space. Every Fréchet space is a Ptak space. 
The strong bidual (that is, the strong dual space of the strong dual space) of a metrizable locally convex space is a Fréchet space. 

===Norms and normability===

If formula_1 is a locally convex space then the topology of formula_1 can be a defined by a family of continuous on formula_1 (a norm is a positive-definite seminorm) if and only if there exists continuous on formula_88 
Even if a Fréchet space has a topology that is defined by a (countable) family of (all norms are also seminorms), then it may nevertheless still fail to be normable space (meaning that its topology can not be defined by any single norm). 
The space of all sequences formula_89 (with the product topology) is a Fréchet space. There does not exist any Hausdorff locally convex topology on formula_89 that is strictly coarser than this product topology. 
The space formula_89 is not normable, which means that its topology can not be defined by any norm. Also, there does not exist continuous norm on formula_92 In fact, as the following theorem shows, whenever formula_1 is a Fréchet space on which there does not exist any continuous norm, then this is due entirely to the presence of formula_89 as a subspace. 

If formula_1 is a non-normable Fréchet space on which there exists a continuous norm, then formula_1 contains a closed vector subspace that has no topological complement. 

A metrizable locally convex space is normable if and only if its strong dual space is a Fréchet–Urysohn locally convex space. In particular, if a locally convex metrizable space formula_1 (such as a Fréchet space) is normable (which can only happen if formula_1 is infinite dimensional) then its strong dual space formula_99 is not a Fréchet–Urysohn space and consequently, this complete Hausdorff locally convex space formula_99 is also neither metrizable nor normable.

The strong dual space of a Fréchet space (and more generally, of bornological spaces such as metrizable TVSs) is always a complete TVS and so like any complete TVS, it is normable if and only if its topology can be induced by a complete norm (that is, if and only if it can be made into a Banach space that has the same topology). 
If formula_1 is a Fréchet space then formula_1 is normable if (and only if) there exists a complete norm on its continuous dual space formula_103 such that the norm induced topology on formula_103 is finer than the weak-* topology. 
Consequently, if a Fréchet space is normable (which can only happen if it is infinite dimensional) then neither is its strong dual space. 

===Anderson–Kadec theorem===

Note that the homeomorphism described in the Anderson–Kadec theorem is necessarily linear. 

==Differentiation of functions==
If formula_1 and formula_106 are Fréchet spaces, then the space formula_107 consisting of all continuous linear maps from formula_1 to formula_106 is a Fréchet space in any natural manner. This is a major difference between the theory of Banach spaces and that of Fréchet spaces and necessitates a different definition for continuous differentiability of functions defined on Fréchet spaces, the Gateaux derivative:

Suppose formula_14 is an open subset of a Fréchet space formula_111 formula_112 is a function valued in a Fréchet space formula_113 formula_114 and formula_115 The map formula_116 is differentiable at formula_20 in the direction formula_118 if the limit
formula_119
exists. 
The map formula_116 is said to be continuously differentiable in formula_14 if the map
formula_122
is continuous. Since the product of Fréchet spaces is again a Fréchet space, we can then try to differentiate formula_123 and define the higher derivatives of formula_116 in this fashion. 

The derivative operator formula_125 defined by formula_126 is itself infinitely differentiable. The first derivative is given by
formula_127
for any two elements formula_128 
This is a major advantage of the Fréchet space formula_129 over the Banach space formula_130 for finite formula_131 

If formula_112 is a continuously differentiable function, then the differential equation
formula_133
need not have any solutions, and even if does, the solutions need not be unique. This is in stark contrast to the situation in Banach spaces. 

In general, the inverse function theorem is not true in Fréchet spaces, although a partial substitute is the Nash–Moser theorem.

==Fréchet manifolds and Lie groups==
One may define Fréchet manifolds as spaces that &quot;locally look like&quot; Fréchet spaces (just like ordinary manifolds are defined as spaces that locally look like Euclidean space formula_134), and one can then extend the concept of Lie group to these manifolds. 
This is useful because for a given (ordinary) compact formula_135 manifold formula_136 the set of all formula_135 diffeomorphisms formula_138 forms a generalized Lie group in this sense, and this Lie group captures the symmetries of formula_82 
Some of the relations between Lie algebras and Lie groups remain valid in this setting.

Another important example of a Fréchet Lie group is the loop group of a compact Lie group formula_140 the smooth (formula_135) mappings formula_142 multiplied pointwise by formula_143

==Generalizations==

If we drop the requirement for the space to be locally convex, we obtain F-spaces: vector spaces with complete translation-invariant metrics.

LF-spaces are countable inductive limits of Fréchet spaces.

